      <back>
        <div type="commentary" corresp="#rvf001">
            <note type="introduction">
                The first poem of the <title level="m">Rvf</title>, <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">Voi ch’ascoltate</foreign> constitutes all-important declarations of the fragmentary nature of the poems that will follow and of the poet’s regret for the vanity and worthlessness of  ch’ascoltatehis worldly concerns and pursuit of fame and earthly love, or his <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">giovenile errore</foreign>, which Petrarch’s early copyist, Giovanni Boccaccio, read as <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">giovenile errore</foreign> (see variants). This introductory poems sits, of course, directly below the rubricated announcement of — in order — the poet (<foreign xml:lang="lat" rendition="#i">Francisci Petrarche</foreign>), his fame as a crowned poet laureate (<foreign xml:lang="lat" rendition="#i">laureati poete</foreign>) and the title of the work (<title level="m">Rerum vulgarium fragmenta</title>): Francisci Petrarche laureati poete.Rerum vulgarium fragmenta (<ref target="c001r.xml"><title>Petrarchive</title> c. 1r</ref>).
            </note>
          <note type="prosody" resp="#hws">
            Sonnet: ABBA ABBA CDE CDE.
          </note>
            <note type="syntax">
                While many editions prefer a medial pause (: or ;) at the end of vv. 4 and 11 (rather than our brief pauses (,), it is clear that the sonnet’s syntax is organized along two full syntactic stops (.) that define the octave (vv. 1–8) and the sestet (9–14), a division that is also reiterated by the adversative conjunction <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">Ma</foreign> at the opening of v. 9 and reinforced by the adverb and verb of perception (<foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">ben veggio</foreign>) that clarifies the contrast (also in the first syntactic unit) between the introductory sonnet’s predominant present tense (<foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">ascoltate, spero, veggio, mi vergogno, è</foreign>) and the poet’s past (<foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">io nudriva,</foreign> [<foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">io</foreign>] <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">era, fui</foreign>). 
            </note>
          <note type="genesis" resp="#hws">
            <!-- tag all non-English text as <foreign xml:lang="xxx">. For italicized text, add rendition="#i". -->
              The <foreign xml:lang="lat" rendition="#i">exordium</foreign> to the song book, the first sonnet introduces the notion of audience (<foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">Voi</foreign> [assigned later in diverse contexts to Laura), the poetic “I” from youth (<foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">giovenile errore</foreign>) and its changes to adulthood (<foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">era … altr’ uom da quel ch’i’ sono</foreign>) and the reflection and shame in older age (<foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">Favola fui … mi vergogno … vergogna è ’l frutto</foreign>), and multiple styles (<foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">Del vario stile</foreign>) and devices (<foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">rime sparse</foreign>) by borrowing from both classical and vernacular sources, especially notions dear to <foreign xml:lang="ita">Due-</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="ita">Trecento stilnovisti</foreign>: <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">sospiri, piango e ragiono,</foreign> the initiates of love (<foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">chi per prova intenda amore</foreign>). Attempts to date the sonnet’s original composition vary from as early as 1347 to 1350. These dates are all based, however, on conjectures about the conceptualization of the <title level="m">Rvf</title> as a book project. While absent from the draft MS Vaticano Latino 3196, the earliest attestation of the sonnet’s role as the introductory poem to the work is found in Boccaccio’s transcription of the <foreign xml:lang="lat" rendition="#i">Fragmentorum liber</foreign>, MS Chigiano L v 176, cc. 43v–79r, where Boccaccio reads: <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">In sul mio primo giovenile amore</foreign> (c. 43v, Rvf 1,3).
          </note>
          <note type="diplomatics" resp="#hws">
              In MS Vaticano Latino 3195, c. 1r begins with the rubric <foreign xml:lang="lat" rendition="#i">Francisci petrarche laureati poete. Rerum vulgarium fragmenta</foreign>, and establishes three key principles of the physical and material construction of the <title level="m">Rvf</title> 1: the poetic ‘canvas’ of 31 transcriptional lines per side of each charta; 2: the horizontal mise en page of the sonnet, written 2 verses per transcriptional line on 7 lines, and 3: the standard presentation of four sonnets per charta each separated by a single blank line (= 7 + 1 + 7 + 1 + 7 + 1 + 7; see Appendix Glossary: <ref target="glossary.xml#sonnet">Sonnet</ref> and <ref target="glossary.xml#transcriptional_canvas">Transcriptional Canvas</ref>).  These first four sonnets on c. 1r constitute an ‘introduction’ (that includes <title level="m">Rvf</title> 5 on c. 1v) to the poet, Love’s ambush of Petrarch, Laura, Laura’s birthplace, Laura’s name and Petrarch’s inspiration. Within the arc in the role of <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">Voi</foreign> from <title level="m">Rvf</title> 1.1 to <title level="m">Rvf</title> 5.1, we note the significant movement from <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">Voi ch’ascoltate</foreign> … to <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">Quando io movo i sospiri a chiamar voi.</foreign>
          </note>
          <note type="variants" resp="#hws">
            <list>
              <item>v. 3: <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">giovenile amore</foreign> (Vaticano Chigiano L V 176).</item>
            </list>
          </note>
          <note type="language" resp="#hws">
              <list>
                  <item>v. 2. <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">io nudriva</foreign>: common first person in the imperfect in the <foreign xml:lang="ita">Due-</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="ita">Trecento</foreign> (also in v. 4: <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">Quand’ era … altr’uom da quel ch’i’ sono</foreign>);</item>
              <item>v. 5. <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">ragiono</foreign>: <foreign xml:lang="ita">‘parlo’</foreign> or in this context <foreign xml:lang="ita">‘canto’</foreign> in modern Italian;</item>
                  <item>v. 6. repetition of the adj. <foreign xml:lang="ita">vano</foreign> is echoed in v. 12 (<foreign xml:lang="ita">vaneggiar</foreign>) and connects the hopelessness of <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">vane speranze</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">van dolore</foreign> to the intensity of the poet’s shame (vv. 11–12);</item>
                  <item>v. 11. note the multiple forms of the first person reflexive; <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">meco</foreign>: <foreign xml:lang="ita">con me stesso</foreign>.</item>
              </list>     
          </note>
          <note type="thematics" resp="#hws">
              Poetics: Petrarch's <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">rime sparse</foreign> and the very sound (<foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">suono</foreign>) of his verses are equated with the <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">sospiri</foreign> popular in Stilnovist, or more specifically the poetic vocabularies of Guido Cavalcanti and Dante Alighieri, as part of youth’s vain love (vv. 1-4); this same poetics is recalled in the poetic formulae: <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">piango e ragiono</foreign> (5), <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">chi per prova intenda amore</foreign> (7), both Dantean and in diverse poetic contexts (see, for ex., <title level="m">Inf.</title> 5. and the opening verse of the canzone <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">Donne ch’avete intelletto d’amore</foreign> in the <title level="m">Vita nova</title>). The sonnet proposes change from the poet’s former self (esp. v. 4) through reflection and subsequent shame and regret over the vanity of worldly love and the vain fame that only results in shame (vv. 6-12) before a public or audience that he addresses directly in the opening vocative <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">Voi</foreign> (1) both public (<foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">al popol tutto</foreign> [9]) but that also constitutes the private audience of Laura (see <title level="m">Rvf</title> 5.1: “Quando io movo i sospiri a chiamar <foreign xml:lang="ita" rendition="#i">voi</foreign>”).
          </note>
          <note type="translation">
              <ab>You who listen in scattered rhymes to the sound / of those sighs with which I nourished my heart / in my early youthful error, / when I was in part another man than who I am now; in the various styles in which I weep and sing / among vain hopes and hopeless pain, / where he who by experience understands love, / I hope to find compassion if not forgiveness. But well I see now just how to the public / I was a myth for so long; where often / I feel within myself such shame of myself: / and of my hopeless life whose fruit is shame, / and the pardon I seek and knowing clearly that what pleases the world is nothing but a brief dream.  
            </ab>
          </note>
        </div>
      </back>
